  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'सर्पचरा (Sarpachara)', englishName: 'Oriental Darter', scientificName: 'Anhinga melanogaster', habitat: 'Rivers', conservationStatus: 'Near Threatened', description: 'Snake-necked diving bird that spears fish with its sharp bill. Unlike ducks, its feathers are not waterproof so it must spread its wings to dry after diving.', funFact: 'The oriental darter spears fish underwater with a lightning-fast strike triggered by a specialised hinge mechanism in its neck vertebrae — the strike takes just 75 milliseconds.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'कालो घाँटी सारस', englishName: 'Black-necked Stork', scientificName: 'Ephippiorhynchus asiaticus', habitat: 'Marsh and rivers', conservationStatus: 'Near Threatened', description: 'Tall stork with a striking black neck and iridescent green-and-purple head. Males have brown eyes; females have bright yellow eyes.', funFact: 'Black-necked stork pairs are thought to mate for life and return to the same nest each year, adding sticks to it until nests can weigh over 200 kg.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'सानो सिठ्ठी हाँस', englishName: 'Lesser Whistling Duck', scientificName: 'Dendrocygna javanica', habitat: 'Wetlands', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Duck named for its whistling call in flight. Unlike most ducks it nests in tree cavities.', funFact: 'Lesser whistling ducks fly nocturnally in large flocks and navigate by starlight. They roost in trees rather than on water — unusual behaviour for a duck.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'धर्के टाउके हाँस', englishName: 'Bar-headed Goose', scientificName: 'Anser indicus', habitat: 'Rivers', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Migrates over the Himalayas twice yearly, flying over peaks above 7,000 m. In winter it uses CNP\'s rivers as a stopover.', funFact: 'Bar-headed geese cross the Himalayas in a single flight, climbing from near sea level to over 7,000 m in just 8 hours — the fastest high-altitude ascent of any bird.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'रुडी हाँस (Rudi Hans)', englishName: 'Ruddy Shelduck', scientificName: 'Tadorna ferruginea', habitat: 'Riverbanks', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Orange-brown duck revered in Buddhist culture as a symbol of fidelity. It nests in rock crevices and tree holes far from water.', funFact: 'Ruddy shelducks are sacred in Buddhist culture and appear in Tibetan art. Mated pairs call to each other constantly — males and females have distinctly different calls used in duets.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'कपासे हाँस (Kapase Hans)', englishName: 'Cotton Pygmy Goose', scientificName: 'Nettapus coromandelianus', habitat: 'Lakes', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Very small waterfowl — one of the smallest ducks in the world. Despite its tiny size it is a strong flier and migrates considerable distances.', funFact: 'The cotton pygmy goose weighs only 160 grams — smaller than a can of soda — making it one of the three smallest waterfowl species in the world.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'ठूलो राजा माछाचरा', englishName: 'Stork-billed Kingfisher', scientificName: 'Pelargopsis capensis', habitat: 'Rivers', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Huge-billed kingfisher with loud raucous calls. It is one of the largest kingfishers in the world and can catch fish larger than its own head.', funFact: 'The stork-billed kingfisher has a bill so large relative to its body that early naturalists thought it was a separate species from the head and body.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'सेतो घाँटी राजा माछाचरा', englishName: 'White-throated Kingfisher', scientificName: 'Halcyon smyrnensis', habitat: 'Wetlands', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Bright blue-and-brown kingfisher found throughout CNP. Unlike most kingfishers it often hunts far from water, taking grasshoppers, geckos, and frogs.', funFact: 'The white-throated kingfisher\'s call inspired the noise of the futuristic guns in the original Star Wars films — sound designers recorded this bird and pitched it down electronically.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'साधारण राजा माछाचरा', englishName: 'Common Kingfisher', scientificName: 'Alcedo atthis', habitat: 'Streams', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Small blue-and-orange jewel of CNP\'s rivers. It can spot fish from 1 metre above water, accounting for the light refraction, and dives with pinpoint accuracy.', funFact: 'The kingfisher\'s streamlined beak inspired the nose of Japan\'s Shinkansen bullet train — copying its shape eliminated the sonic boom that occurred when the train exited tunnels.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'चिते राजा माछाचरा', englishName: 'Pied Kingfisher', scientificName: 'Ceryle rudis', habitat: 'Lakes', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Hovers in place before diving — the only kingfisher in the world that regularly hunts by hovering.', funFact: 'The pied kingfisher is the world\'s largest bird that can hunt by hovering — it can hold position in still air for up to 20 seconds before diving at fish below.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'नीलो घाँटी पिट्टा', englishName: 'Blue-throated Pitta', scientificName: 'Hydrornis nipalensis', habitat: 'Dense forest', conservationStatus: 'Vulnerable', description: 'Colourful forest bird with brilliant green, blue, and red plumage. Nepal is the only country where it breeds.', funFact: 'The blue-throated pitta was scientifically described from a specimen collected in Nepal in 1836 — it is named "nipalensis" after the country and Nepal is its global breeding headquarters.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'स्वर्गीय चरा (Swargiya Chara)', englishName: 'Indian Paradise Flycatcher', scientificName: 'Terpsiphone paradisi', habitat: 'Forest', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Long flowing tail makes the male unmistakable in CNP\'s forests. Males can be either white or rufous-orange.', funFact: 'The male Indian paradise flycatcher\'s tail streamers grow up to 24 cm long — three times the length of its body — and are shed after the breeding season to reduce drag during migration.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'ठूलो कठफोडवा', englishName: 'Great Slaty Woodpecker', scientificName: 'Mulleripicus pulverulentus', habitat: 'Tall forest', conservationStatus: 'Vulnerable', description: 'Largest woodpecker in Asia. It requires old-growth tall trees and is a reliable indicator of healthy, mature forest in CNP.', funFact: 'The great slaty woodpecker hammers trees at 20 impacts per second — its brain is surrounded by a specialised spongy bone that absorbs the force of each impact.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'धारिलो घाँटी कठफोडवा', englishName: 'Streak-throated Woodpecker', scientificName: 'Picus xanthopygaeus', habitat: 'Woodland', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Greenish woodpecker common in CNP\'s mixed forests. It forages on ant-rich trees and uses its extraordinarily long, sticky tongue to extract insects from bark.', funFact: 'A woodpecker\'s tongue is so long it wraps around the inside of its skull when retracted — the tongue of this species is nearly 3 times the length of its bill.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'रातो टाउके ट्रोगन', englishName: 'Red-headed Trogon', scientificName: 'Harpactes erythrocephalus', habitat: 'Forest', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Brilliantly coloured red-and-green bird that sits motionless for long periods before sallying out to catch insects.', funFact: 'Trogons have unusual feet with two toes facing forward and two back (arranged differently from parrots), making them awkward walkers but perfect for perching and gripping branches.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'कालो बाज (Kalo Baja)', englishName: 'Black Baza', scientificName: 'Aviceda leuphotes', habitat: 'Woodland', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Small crested hawk with striking black, white, and chestnut plumage. It is a migratory raptor that passes through CNP in large flocks during autumn.', funFact: 'Black bazas migrate in spectacular flocks of up to 1,000 birds, sweeping through forests together and hunting insects flushed by the movement of the flock.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'माछा बाज (Machha Baja)', englishName: 'Grey-headed Fish Eagle', scientificName: 'Icthyophaga ichthyaetus', habitat: 'Rivers', conservationStatus: 'Near Threatened', description: 'Fish-eating eagle that perches above CNP\'s rivers and drops onto fish near the surface. Its rough-soled talons help grip slippery fish.', funFact: 'The grey-headed fish eagle has serrated scales on the soles of its feet — like non-slip pads — specifically evolved to prevent fish from wriggling free after capture.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'रूफस पेटे चील', englishName: 'Rufous-bellied Eagle', scientificName: 'Lophotriorchis kienerii', habitat: 'Forest', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Medium-sized forest eagle with a distinctive rufous belly. It hunts by ambushing birds from forest perches, using the element of surprise.', funFact: 'The rufous-bellied eagle is one of the few raptors that regularly hunts other raptors — it has been observed catching smaller owls and kestrels in mid-air above the forest canopy.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'सानो गिद्ध (Sano Giddha)', englishName: 'Lesser Adjutant Stork', scientificName: 'Leptoptilos javanicus', habitat: 'Marshland', conservationStatus: 'Vulnerable', description: 'Large bare-headed stork that feeds on fish, frogs, and carrion in CNP\'s wetlands. Its bald head is an adaptation for feeding inside carcasses.', funFact: 'The lesser adjutant can swallow prey as large as a small snake whole. Its naked head stays cleaner when feeding inside carcasses — the same reason vultures lack head feathers.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'चित्रे सारस (Chitre Saras)', englishName: 'Painted Stork', scientificName: 'Mycteria leucocephala', habitat: 'Lakes', conservationStatus: 'Near Threatened', description: 'Pink-white stork with a distinctive yellow bill and pink wing patches. It uses a tactile method to catch fish — sweeping its open bill through water.', funFact: 'Painted storks use a fishing technique called "tactolocation" — they walk through shallow water with bills held open, snapping shut the instant they touch a fish, without needing to see it.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'कालो पेटे टर्न', englishName: 'Black-bellied Tern', scientificName: 'Sterna acuticauda', habitat: 'River islands', conservationStatus: 'Endangered', description: 'River-nesting tern that breeds on sandy islands in CNP\'s rivers. It is increasingly threatened by river sand-mining and flooding of nesting beaches.', funFact: 'The black-bellied tern nests directly on bare sand with no nest structure — the eggs are speckled to match the sand perfectly, making them almost invisible from above.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'कालो चिल (Kalo Chil)', englishName: 'Black Kite', scientificName: 'Milvus migrans', habitat: 'Open areas', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Common scavenger bird seen soaring over CNP\'s buffer zone and villages. It is one of the most abundant raptors in the world.', funFact: 'Black kites have learned to deliberately pick up burning sticks from wildfires and drop them in unburned grass to start new fires — flushing out prey. One of very few documented tool-use behaviours in birds.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'दलदली तीतर (Daldali Titar)', englishName: 'Swamp Francolin', scientificName: 'Ortygornis gularis', habitat: 'Tall grass', conservationStatus: 'Vulnerable', description: 'Secretive grassland bird of CNP\'s tall phanta grasslands. It is rarely seen but often heard calling from dense cover in the early morning.', funFact: 'Swamp francolins are among the few birds that drink standing in water while calling — their resonant calls carry much farther across wetlands when projected from water level.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'लामो खुट्टे जकाना', englishName: 'Pheasant-tailed Jacana', scientificName: 'Hydrophasianus chirurgus', habitat: 'Marsh', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Walks on floating aquatic plants using its extraordinarily long toes which spread its weight. In breeding plumage the tail elongates dramatically.', funFact: 'In the pheasant-tailed jacana sex roles are reversed — females are larger, hold territories, and court males. The smaller males incubate the eggs and raise the chicks alone.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'काँसे जकाना', englishName: 'Bronze-winged Jacana', scientificName: 'Metopidius indicus', habitat: 'Swamps', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Metallic bronze-winged bird that walks on lily pads. It carries its chicks under its wings with only their legs dangling visibly.', funFact: 'When danger approaches, a bronze-winged jacana father scoops all four chicks under his wings and runs — observers often see a bird running with four tiny legs dangling beneath its wings.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'सारस (Saras)', englishName: 'Sarus Crane', scientificName: 'Antigone antigone', habitat: 'Floodplains', conservationStatus: 'Vulnerable', description: 'Tallest flying bird in the world, reaching 1.8 m. Pairs bond for life and perform elaborate synchronised dancing displays.', funFact: 'Sarus crane pairs are famously devoted. Historical accounts describe surviving partners calling mournfully for weeks after losing a mate — they are celebrated in South Asian literature as symbols of true love.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'डेमोइसेल सारस', englishName: 'Demoiselle Crane', scientificName: 'Anthropoides virgo', habitat: 'Open plains', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Elegant migratory crane that passes through Nepal twice yearly crossing the Himalayas. It is the smallest crane species in the world.', funFact: 'Demoiselle cranes cross the Himalayas in V-formations at altitudes over 8,000 m — they have been recorded flying over Mount Everest during autumn migration.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'कालो ड्रोंगो (Kalo Drongo)', englishName: 'Black Drongo', scientificName: 'Dicrurus macrocercus', habitat: 'Open land', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Aggressive insect-eating bird that fearlessly mobs crows, kites, and even eagles many times its size to defend its territory.', funFact: 'Black drongos act as "false alarm" birds — they mimic the alarm calls of other species to scare them away from food sources, then swoop in to steal the abandoned insects.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'जंगल मैना (Jungle Maina)', englishName: 'Jungle Myna', scientificName: 'Acridotheres fuscus', habitat: 'Forest edge', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Noisy social bird found along CNP\'s forest edges. It forages in groups, often following large animals to catch insects flushed from grass.', funFact: 'Jungle mynas follow grazing animals like a shadow — research shows a single myna bird can catch up to 4 times more insects per hour by following a buffalo than by foraging alone.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'पहाडी मैना (Pahadi Maina)', englishName: 'Common Hill Myna', scientificName: 'Gracula religiosa', habitat: 'Forest', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Excellent mimic capable of reproducing human speech with remarkable accuracy. It is the best talking bird in the world, arguably surpassing even parrots.', funFact: 'The hill myna can reproduce human speech at exactly the right pitch and timbre — unlike parrots that shift pitch, mynas mimic the precise voice quality of the specific person they heard.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'छाती रातो बाबलर', englishName: 'Chestnut-capped Babbler', scientificName: 'Timalia pileata', habitat: 'Shrubs', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Small group bird found in dense shrubs. It moves in tight family groups through tangled vegetation.', funFact: 'Chestnut-capped babblers are cooperative breeders — the whole family group helps raise the chicks of the dominant pair, with siblings acting as babysitters and food-providers.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'लामो चोचो बाबलर', englishName: 'Slender-billed Babbler', scientificName: 'Turdoides longirostris', habitat: 'Grass scrub', conservationStatus: 'Vulnerable', description: 'Rare grassland bird dependent on tall grass habitat. CNP\'s phanta grasslands are one of its last known strongholds in Nepal.', funFact: 'The slender-billed babbler uses its unusually long, curved bill to probe deep into grass stems and pull out insects — a foraging technique not seen in any other babbler species.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'बालुवाको चरा', englishName: 'Indian Sand Lark', scientificName: 'Alaudala raytal', habitat: 'Sandy rivers', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Small ground bird that nests and forages exclusively on sandy riverbanks. Its pale sandy colouration provides perfect camouflage against bare river sand.', funFact: 'The Indian sand lark is so precisely colour-matched to river sand that nesting birds become invisible from just 2 metres away — researchers often locate nests only by accidentally almost stepping on them.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'कालो घाँटी बाबलर', englishName: 'Black-throated Babbler', scientificName: 'Stachyris nigricollis', habitat: 'Dense forest', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Understory insect-eater found in CNP\'s dense sal forest understorey. It forages in mixed-species flocks, benefiting from the safety in numbers.', funFact: 'Mixed-species foraging flocks, which this babbler joins, can contain up to 30 different bird species all moving together — the flock reduces individual predation risk by 80%.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'कोइली (Koili)', englishName: 'Common Hawk-Cuckoo', scientificName: 'Hierococcyx varius', habitat: 'Forest', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Famous for its repetitive rising call described as "brain-fever, brain-fever" which increases in pace and pitch during the hot season. A brood parasite of babblers.', funFact: 'The hawk-cuckoo chick hatches before the host\'s eggs and immediately pushes them out of the nest — it then mimics the calls of multiple hungry chicks to stimulate extra feeding by the foster parent.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'सेतो घाँटी फ्यान्टेल', englishName: 'White-throated Fantail', scientificName: 'Rhipidura albicollis', habitat: 'Forest', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Constantly fans and flicks its tail while foraging, flushing insects from leaves. It is one of the most energetic and restless small birds in CNP.', funFact: 'White-throated fantails never stop moving — research shows they change position an average of once every 2 seconds while foraging, constantly fanning the tail to startle hidden insects.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'नीलो घाँटी बारबेट', englishName: 'Blue-throated Barbet', scientificName: 'Psilopogon asiaticus', habitat: 'Trees', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Loud fruit-eating bird with a repetitive "kutroo-kutroo" call. It excavates nest holes in tree trunks which are later used by other cavity-nesting species.', funFact: 'Blue-throated barbets are accidental foresters — they eat large fruits whole and defecate seeds far from parent trees, inadvertently planting hundreds of trees each year.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'भारतीय रोलर', englishName: 'Indian Roller', scientificName: 'Coracias benghalensis', habitat: 'Grassland', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Brilliant blue flight display makes this bird unmistakable. It is the state bird of Karnataka, Odisha, and Andhra Pradesh.', funFact: 'The Indian roller\'s iridescent blue wing colours are not pigment-based — they are created by microscopic structures in the feather barbules that scatter specific wavelengths of light, like a prism.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'चित्ते स्टार्लिंग', englishName: 'Spot-winged Starling', scientificName: 'Saroglossa spilopterus', habitat: 'Forest edge', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Black bird with distinctive white spots on its wings. A migratory species that visits CNP\'s forest edges seasonally, feeding on nectar and small fruits.', funFact: 'Spot-winged starlings are key pollinators of several large flowering trees — they hover like hummingbirds to reach flowers and transfer pollen on their foreheads between blooms.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'घर भँगेरा (Ghar Bhagera)', englishName: 'House Sparrow', scientificName: 'Passer domesticus', habitat: 'Settlements', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Common near human settlements in CNP\'s buffer zone. House sparrow populations have declined dramatically in cities worldwide.', funFact: 'House sparrows have lived alongside humans for over 10,000 years and have physically changed as a result — their beaks became shorter and stronger to eat the grains grown in early human agriculture.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'पहेंलो छाती बुन्टिङ', englishName: 'Yellow-breasted Bunting', scientificName: 'Emberiza aureola', habitat: 'Grassland', conservationStatus: 'Critically Endangered', description: 'Rapidly declining migratory bird. Illegal trapping for food in East Asia has caused a 90% population decline since 1980.', funFact: 'The yellow-breasted bunting was once so abundant it was called the "rice bird". Hunting has reduced global numbers from 100 million to under 1 million in 40 years.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'सेतो छाती जलकाग', englishName: 'White-breasted Waterhen', scientificName: 'Amaurornis phoenicurus', habitat: 'Marshes', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Common wetland rail with a loud, almost comically repetitive call. It walks through marshes flicking its tail.', funFact: 'The white-breasted waterhen\'s dawn call is one of the most persistent sounds in CNP — it calls a single note up to 60 times per minute for up to an hour, unmistakably announcing the day.'),
];

// ── FISH (6) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const List<SpeciesInfo> fish = [
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'सहार (Sahar)', englishName: 'Golden Mahseer', scientificName: 'Tor putitora', habitat: 'Clear, fast-flowing rivers', conservationStatus: 'Endangered', description: 'Nepal\'s national fish and the "tiger of the rivers". CNP\'s Narayani River is one of its last strongholds. Anglers travel worldwide to fish for mahseer in these waters.', funFact: 'Golden mahseer can live for over 30 years and grow to 2.75 m and 54 kg — making them one of the largest freshwater fish in Asia and a living testament to the health of CNP\'s rivers.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'भोटे सहार', englishName: 'Chocolate Mahseer', scientificName: 'Neolissochilus hexagonolepis', habitat: 'Deep, cold river pools', conservationStatus: 'Vulnerable', description: 'Large powerful river fish with distinctive dark-edged hexagonal scales. It migrates upstream during monsoon to spawn in the cooler Himalayan foothill rivers.', funFact: 'Chocolate mahseer undertake seasonal migrations of over 200 km upstream to spawn — one of the longest freshwater fish migrations recorded in South Asia.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'रोहु (Rohu)', englishName: 'Rohu Carp', scientificName: 'Labeo rohita', habitat: 'Slow-moving rivers and floodplain lakes', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'One of the most important freshwater fish in South Asia. In CNP it inhabits the deeper pools of the Rapti and Narayani rivers, feeding on decaying organic matter.', funFact: 'Rohu are among the cleanest fish in rivers — they feed specifically on decomposing organic matter and algae, acting as natural water purifiers that reduce algae blooms.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'असला (Asala)', englishName: 'Snow Trout (Asala)', scientificName: 'Schizothorax progastus', habitat: 'Cold, clear hill streams', conservationStatus: 'Near Threatened', description: 'Himalayan snow trout found in cooler streams at CNP\'s northern margins. Its hard, cartilaginous lip edge is adapted for scraping algae from fast-flowing rocky streams.', funFact: 'Snow trout have lips with a hard scraping edge unique among fish — functioning like a razor blade to scrape biofilm from rocks in torrential streams where no other fish can feed.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'मागुर (Magur)', englishName: 'Walking Catfish', scientificName: 'Clarias batrachus', habitat: 'Ponds, ditches, rice paddies', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Walking catfish can breathe air using a specialised labyrinth organ and "walk" overland on its pectoral fins for hundreds of metres to reach new water bodies.', funFact: 'Walking catfish can survive out of water for up to 18 hours and have been found crossing roads, entering rice paddies, and colonising ponds with no stream connections — true cross-country explorers.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'बाम (Bam)', englishName: 'Striped Snakehead', scientificName: 'Channa striata', habitat: 'Wetlands, oxbow lakes', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Powerful air-breathing predatory fish that ambushes prey from dense aquatic vegetation in CNP\'s oxbow lakes. Both parents guard the floating nest and school of fry.', funFact: 'Snakehead fish are devoted parents — both parents herd their fry in a tight school for weeks after hatching, attacking anything that approaches, including hands several times their size.'),
];

// ── REPTILES (12) ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const List<SpeciesInfo> reptiles = [
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'घारियाल', englishName: 'Gharial', scientificName: 'Gavialis gangeticus', habitat: 'Large rivers (Narayani, Rapti)', conservationStatus: 'Critically Endangered', description: 'Long-snouted river crocodile and fish specialist. CNP\'s Narayani River is one of the last breeding sites for this species. Fewer than 1,000 remain in the wild globally.', funFact: 'The "ghara" (pot-shaped bump) on the male\'s snout tip amplifies hissing sounds and visual signals during courtship — and it keeps growing throughout the male\'s life, so older males have bigger gharas.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'मगर', englishName: 'Mugger Crocodile', scientificName: 'Crocodylus palustris', habitat: 'Rivers, oxbow lakes, wetlands', conservationStatus: 'Vulnerable', description: 'Marsh and river crocodile common in CNP\'s wetlands and oxbow lakes. It basks on sandy banks for hours and can make explosive short-burst sprints on land.', funFact: 'Mugger crocodiles have been observed balancing sticks on their snouts near bird nesting colonies to lure nest-building birds — one of the very few documented tool-use behaviours in reptiles.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'अजिंगर', englishName: 'Indian Rock Python', scientificName: 'Python molurus', habitat: 'Forests, grassland edges', conservationStatus: 'Near Threatened', description: 'Large non-venomous constrictor that preys on mammals and birds in CNP. It can exceed 6 m in length and can go over a year without eating after consuming a large meal.', funFact: 'After eating a large deer, an Indian python slows its heartbeat, shrinks its organs, and reduces its metabolism by 70% — essentially going into a hibernation-like state while digesting.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'अजिंगर (भी ठूलो)', englishName: 'Burmese Rock Python', scientificName: 'Python bivittatus', habitat: 'Forests near water', conservationStatus: 'Near Threatened', description: 'Very large python often recorded in CNP\'s Terai wetlands and grasslands. One of the five largest snakes on Earth, capable of reaching 6-7 m in length.', funFact: 'Burmese pythons have heat-sensing pits along their lips that detect temperature differences as small as 0.003°C — allowing them to "see" warm-blooded prey in complete darkness.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'कोब्रा (साँप)', englishName: 'King Cobra', scientificName: 'Ophiophagus hannah', habitat: 'Forest and forest edge', conservationStatus: 'Vulnerable', description: 'World\'s longest venomous snake, reaching up to 5.5 m in CNP. It preys almost exclusively on other snakes and is the only snake that builds a nest for its eggs.', funFact: 'A king cobra\'s venom delivery is powerful enough to kill an elephant — and it is the only snake that actively builds a nest, coiling around the egg pile and guarding it until hatching.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'साँप (सामान्य)', englishName: 'Common Krait', scientificName: 'Bungarus caeruleus', habitat: 'Grasslands, edges, near water', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Highly venomous nocturnal snake responsible for many snakebite deaths in South Asia. Its venom blocks nerve signals, causing paralysis.', funFact: 'The common krait is 16 times more venomous than the Indian cobra, but bites are rarely felt at night — its neurotoxic venom causes painless paralysis during sleep, often fatally misdiagnosed as a dream.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'नाग (साँप)', englishName: 'Yellow-striped Water Snake', scientificName: 'Fowlea / Xenochrophis spp.', habitat: 'Wetland margins', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Semi-aquatic non-venomous snake often seen near water in CNP. It actively hunts frogs and fish in the shallows of rivers and wetlands.', funFact: 'Water keelback snakes can eat toads that are toxic to most predators — they have evolved partial immunity to the toxic skin secretions of the common Indian toad.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'गोहिएको सर्प / बाँदर साँप', englishName: 'Oriental Vine Snake', scientificName: 'Ahaetulla nasuta', habitat: 'Shrub and forest edge', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Slender arboreal snake that is mildly venomous. Its elongated, pointed snout and horizontal pupils give it binocular vision — extremely rare in snakes.', funFact: 'The oriental vine snake has horizontal keyhole-shaped pupils giving it stereoscopic (3D) vision — a unique adaptation among snakes that allows it to judge distances precisely for catching fast-moving lizards.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'अजिंगर (घासमान)', englishName: 'Indian Monitor Lizard', scientificName: 'Varanus bengalensis', habitat: 'Grassland, forest edges', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Large terrestrial lizard common in CNP\'s grasslands. It uses a forked tongue like snakes to "smell" the air in 3D and can locate buried prey.', funFact: 'Monitor lizards have a Komodo dragon-like venom — a discovery made only in 2009 — but unlike Komodo dragons, Indian monitors rarely bite large prey and rely mainly on speed and agility.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'कालो छेपारो', englishName: 'Oriental Garden Lizard', scientificName: 'Calotes versicolor', habitat: 'Forest edge, grassland', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Diurnal agamid lizard frequently seen basking on rocks and posts in CNP. Males turn brilliant red-and-orange around the throat during territorial displays.', funFact: 'Male garden lizards turn fire-engine red from the neck forward during the breeding season — this colour change is so striking that locals call them "bloodsuckers", though they are completely harmless.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'चक्राकार कछुवा', englishName: 'Indian Narrow-headed Softshell', scientificName: 'Chitra indica', habitat: 'Large river systems', conservationStatus: 'Endangered', description: 'Large softshell turtle in CNP\'s rivers. It buries itself in river sand with only its tiny head exposed, ambushing fish that swim overhead.', funFact: 'The Indian narrow-headed softshell has the smallest head relative to body size of any turtle — its tiny pointed snout protrudes from the sand as a barely visible bump, making it undetectable to fish.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'नरम खोल कछुवा', englishName: 'Indian Softshell Turtle', scientificName: 'Nilssonia gangetica', habitat: 'Rivers and wetlands', conservationStatus: 'Vulnerable', description: 'Freshwater softshell turtle often buried in sand in CNP\'s rivers. Unlike hard-shelled turtles, its flexible shell allows it to squeeze under rocks and into crevices.', funFact: 'Softshell turtles can absorb oxygen directly through specialised skin on their necks — allowing them to stay submerged for hours by "breathing" through their throat skin.'),
];

// ── AMPHIBIANS (6) ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const List<SpeciesInfo> amphibians = [
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'चितवन भ्यागुता', englishName: 'Chitwan Frog', scientificName: 'Hylarana chitwanensis', habitat: 'Terai grasslands, forest edges', conservationStatus: 'Near Threatened', description: 'Endemic lowland frog first scientifically described from Chitwan National Park. This species is found nowhere else in the world and is threatened by habitat loss in the Terai.', funFact: 'The Chitwan frog is named after this very park — it was first described scientifically from specimens collected here, making CNP the type locality for this species.'),
