  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'इम्पेराटा', englishName: 'Imperata Grass', scientificName: 'Imperata cylindrica', habitat: 'Short grasslands', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Common short grass found in CNP\'s open areas and degraded land. While considered a weed in many parts of the world, it provides crucial ground-level cover for small mammals in CNP.', funFact: 'Imperata grass forms underground rhizome networks that can weigh ten times more than the visible above-ground plant — allowing it to regenerate explosively after fire, drought, or cutting.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'फाँट घाँस', englishName: 'Reed Grass', scientificName: 'Phragmites karka', habitat: 'Wetland edges', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Tall reed forming dense stands along CNP\'s marshes and river edges. Its dense stands provide essential nesting habitat for grassland birds and shelter for rhinos and elephants.', funFact: 'Reed grass culms (stems) grow up to 8 cm per day during the monsoon — one of the fastest growth rates of any non-bamboo grass. A single plant can spread to cover 100 square metres in one season.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'खरजोङ', englishName: 'Elephant Apple', scientificName: 'Dillenia indica', habitat: 'Riverine forest', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Riverine tree whose large apple-like fruits are eagerly eaten by elephants, bears, and deer. The fleshy sepals surrounding the fruit are used to make a refreshing drink.', funFact: 'Elephant apple fruits weigh up to 800 g and have such a tough outer coating that only animals with sufficient strength — elephants, bears, and large deer — can open them. Small animals get none.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'भीर गुल्मी', englishName: 'Velvet Beautyberry', scientificName: 'Callicarpa macrophylla', habitat: 'Understorey forest', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Understorey shrub offering berries and shelter in CNP\'s forest understorey. Its clusters of vivid purple berries are an important food source for birds in the dry season.', funFact: 'The beautyberry\'s purple berries contain a natural compound (callicarpenal) that repels mosquitoes and ticks more effectively than DEET in laboratory tests, according to USDA research.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'फूलबुट्टा', englishName: 'Hill Glory Bower', scientificName: 'Clerodendrum spp.', habitat: 'Forest edges', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Flowering climber or shrub found along CNP\'s forest edges. Its tubular flowers are a major nectar source for sunbirds, and it provides dense cover for small mammals.', funFact: 'Glory bower flowers are designed specifically for long-tongued insects and birds — the nectar is hidden 3-4 cm deep in the floral tube, accessible only to sunbirds and hawk-moths with matching proboscis length.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'आमलकी', englishName: 'Indian Gooseberry (Amla)', scientificName: 'Phyllanthus emblica', habitat: 'Mixed forests', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Medicinal fruit tree of CNP\'s forest understorey. Amla is one of the richest natural sources of Vitamin C — its fruit contains 20 times more Vitamin C than an orange.', funFact: 'Amla contains Vitamin C that remains stable after cooking — unlike most Vitamin C sources that are destroyed by heat. Traditional Indian pickle-making preserves the full vitamin content indefinitely.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'आम्र', englishName: 'Wild Mango', scientificName: 'Mangifera indica (wild)', habitat: 'Forest edges', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Wild or semi-wild mango trees found around CNP\'s margins. Wild mangoes produce small, fibrous fruits eagerly consumed by elephants, bears, langurs, and many birds.', funFact: 'Wild mangoes were cultivated in South Asia for over 4,000 years before the familiar large, sweet cultivated varieties were developed. The wild form that elephants enjoy in CNP is essentially unchanged from those ancient trees.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'घाँस विविध', englishName: 'Various Grasses', scientificName: 'Various spp.', habitat: 'Grassland types', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'CNP contains over 50 species of grasses forming its characteristic phanta grasslands. These grasslands are one of the most endangered ecosystems in Asia, making CNP\'s grasslands globally important.', funFact: 'CNP\'s phanta grasslands are among the last remnants of the Terai Arc grassland ecosystem that once stretched across thousands of kilometres of the Himalayan foothills — over 90% has been converted to farmland.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'सत्वा', englishName: 'Kali Musli', scientificName: 'Curculigo orchioides', habitat: 'Forest understorey', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Traditional medicinal herb found in CNP\'s forest understorey. Its black rhizomes are used in Ayurvedic medicine and are in high demand, causing unsustainable collection from wild populations.', funFact: 'This herb\'s rhizomes are so medicinally valued in traditional systems that black-market prices can reach Rs. 5,000 per kg — making illegal harvesting inside protected areas a serious conservation threat.'),
  SpeciesInfo(nepaliName: 'शतावरी', englishName: 'Shatavari (Asparagus)', scientificName: 'Asparagus racemosus', habitat: 'Forest edges', conservationStatus: 'Least Concern', description: 'Medicinal climber extensively used in Ayurvedic and traditional medicine. It scrambles through CNP\'s forest edges, its feathery green branches resembling asparagus foliage.', funFact: 'Shatavari means "she who has a hundred husbands" in Sanskrit — it is considered the foremost women\'s tonic in Ayurveda and is now being investigated scientifically for its adaptogenic properties.'),
